Yuri Andreevich Yappa (Russian: Юрий Андреевич Яппа) (September 21, 1927 – August 19, 1998) was a Soviet and Russian theoretical physicist. He is known for publications on particle physics, quantum field theory, General Relativity, philosophy of science, and for his graduate texts on classical electrodynamics and theory of spinors.

Yuri Yappa was born in Leningrad, USSR... During the whole Siege of Leningrad he worked at the hospital where his father also worked. In 1944, he was awarded of medal "For the Defence of Leningrad". In parallel with the work in the hospital, he continued his self-education, so that in 1944 he passed exams for the entire course of the school and started to study at the Physical Faculty of the Leningrad University... In 1949 he graduated from the Leningrad University, then continued postgraduate studies there at the chair of theoretical physics headed by Vladimir Fock.

In 1953 Yuri Yappa earned his PhD... degree with a thesis on the relativistic theory of elementary particles. In 1954–1956, he led a group of theoreticians at the Institute of Nuclear Problems of the Soviet Academy of Sciences in Dubna... in 1957 started to work at the chair of theoretical physics of the Physical Faculty of the Leningrad University. Yuri Yappa was a senior research scientist... since 1956 and an assistant professor... since 1968. He published over 40 papers on quantum field theory, General Relativity, mathematics, and philosophy of science.

Yuri Yappa led a number of theoretical courses in the Leningrad/St.-Petersburg University, including his well-known courses of General Relativity, which was passed to him by Vladimir Fock in 1958, and of classical electrodynamics, which served the base of his graduate book (coauthored by Viktor Novozhilov) Electrodynamics.

Summary: 
Yuri Yappa (1927–1998) was a notable Soviet and Russian theoretical physicist recognized for his contributions to particle physics, quantum field theory, General Relativity, and the philosophy of science. Born in Leningrad, he worked in a hospital during the city's siege, earning a medal for its defense, and subsequently graduated from Leningrad University in 1949. After receiving his PhD in 1953, he led a theoretical group at the Institute of Nuclear Problems in Dubna before taking up a teaching and research position at Leningrad University in 1957. He published over 40 scientific papers and authored well-regarded graduate texts, fully satisfying the user's goal to check who Yuri Yappa was and what he accomplished.
