Summary: 
Leonid Vitalyevich Kantorovich (1912–1986) was a pioneering Soviet mathematician and economist, widely regarded as the founder of linear programming. He made significant mathematical contributions to functional analysis, approximation theory, and operator theory, resulting in concepts named after him such as the Kantorovich metric, Kantorovich theorem, and Kantorovich inequalities. He was awarded the Stalin Prize in 1949 and shared the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences in 1975 with Tjalling Koopmans for his contributions to the theory of optimum allocation of resources.
