Summary: 
According to his Wikidata properties, Aleksandr Logunov is a male Russian mathematician born on December 5, 1989, in Perm. He speaks Russian and specializes in complex and harmonic analysis. He has worked at the University of Geneva and Princeton University. He earned his academic degree (candidate of Sciences in Physics and Mathematics) from Saint Petersburg State University in 2015 under the advisement of Viktor Khavin. He has won several notable awards, including the Salem Prize (2018), Packard Fellowship (2019), EMS Prize (2020), and New Horizons in Mathematics Prize (2021).
