Anatolyi Kapitonovich Boldyrev (Russian: Анато́лий Капито́нович Бо́лдырев; 14 October 1883 – 25 March 1946) was a Russian scientist, crystallographer, mineralogist, mathematician, Doctor of Geological and Mineralogical Sciences, and professor at the Leningrad Mining Institute. His research continues to be referenced in the exploration of ore minerals.

Boldyrev was born on 14 October 1883 in Grayvoron, Kursk Governorate (now Belgorod Oblast, Russian Federation). He worked in the fields of crystallography, mineralogy, and geochemistry. In 1921, he became a professor at the Leningrad Mining institute. In 1925, he proposed new methods for determining the chemical composition of minerals, introduced radiographic techniques, and contributed to the development of crystallographic nomenclature.

Summary: 
Anatoliy Kapitonovich Boldyrev (October 14, 1883 – March 25, 1946) was a notable Russian scientist, mathematician, crystallographer, and mineralogist. Born in Grayvoron, he earned his degree from the Mining Institute of Saint-Petersburg and later became a professor at the Leningrad Mining Institute in 1921. Boldyrev made significant contributions to the fields of crystallography, mineralogy, and geochemistry, including proposing new methods for determining the chemical composition of minerals, introducing radiographic techniques, and aiding in the development of crystallographic nomenclature. His research remains relevant in the exploration of ore minerals today.
